From several studies, it has been found that approximately there are 140 genes that are responsible for selective growth advantage. These genes are termed as “driver” genes. As mentioned before in the Background, mutations occur in a typical tumor due to two to eight such “driver” genes, while there are only twelve signaling pathways which allow selective growth advantage. These twelve signaling pathways (“target pathways”) are: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
